    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "it makes sense. so like, is it the lactic acid itself that makes them burn, or is it just a signal that the muscle is running out of energy? also why does it feel like it stays there a while before it goes away?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The burning sensation is primarily a result of the accumulation of lactic acid, not the acid itself. Lactic acid is a byproduct of anaerobic metabolism when your muscles need energy quickly, but don't have enough oxygen. When muscles are deprived of oxygen, they produce energy at a high rate, which leads to a buildup of lactic acid. This buildup signals that your muscles are running low on energy and need oxygen to continue working efficiently.\n\nThe feeling of burning lingers because it takes time for your body to process and remove the lactic acid. Your muscles can temporarily store it, and your body must work to convert it back into glucose in your liver or clear it through your bloodstream. This process can take several minutes to an hour after intense exercise, which is why the burning sensation can persist for a while before it finally dissipates.",
